04193nmm a2200649Ia 9781501704093DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20162016nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1002233142  a(OCoLC)1004868529  a(OCoLC)1011439056  a(OCoLC)979743434  a(OCoLC)999355387  a97815017040937 a10.7591/97815017040932doi  a(DE-B1597)478417  a(OCoLC)949878934  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY04a361.6/5094852231 aSchall, Carly Elizabeth, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Rise and Fall of the Miraculous Welfare Machine :bImmigration and Social Democracy in Twentieth-Century Sweden /cCarly Elizabeth Schall. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (258 p.) :b4 tables, 2 charts  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSweden is well known for the success of its welfare state. Many believe that success was made possible in part by the country's ethnic homogeneity and that the increased diversity of Sweden’s population is putting its welfare state at risk. Few, however, have suggested convincing mechanisms for explaining the precise relationship between relative ethnic homogeneity/heterogeneity and the welfare state. In this book Carly Elizabeth Schall acknowledges the important role of ethnic homogeneity in Sweden’s thriving welfare state, but she argues that it mattered primarily because political elites—especially social democrats—made it matter.Schall shows that diversity and the welfare state are related but that diversity does not undermine the welfare state in a straightforward way. Tracing the development of the Swedish welfare state from the late 1920s until the present day, she focuses on five historical periods of crisis. She argues that the story of Swedish national identity is a story of elite-driven hegemony-building and that the linking of social democracy and national identity colored the integration of immigrants in important ways. Social democracy could have withstood the challenge posed by immigration, but the faltering of social democratic hegemony opened a door for anti-immigrant sentiment. In her deft analysis of the relationship between immigration and the welfare state in Sweden, Schall makes a compelling argument that has relevance for immigration policy in the United States and elsewhere.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 4aEurope. 4aPublic Policy. 4aSociology & Social Science.  aSwedish, social democracy, ethnic homogeneity, welfare, national identity.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066749308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2016z9783110485103oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2016z9783110485332oZDB-23-DSW40uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150170409340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501704093423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501704093/original  a978-3-11-066749-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DGGb2016  aZDB-23-DSWb2016